# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: glass-cockpit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:glass-cockpit/2005-in-aviation] This is a list of aviation-related events from 2005.
[src:glass-cockpit/2005-in-aviation] The deadliest crash of this year was West Caribbean Airways Flight 708, a McDonnell Douglas MD-80 which crashed near Machiques, Venezuela on 16 August, killing all 160 people on board.
[src:glass-cockpit/2005-in-aviation] This particular accident took place in August 2005, which is one of the deadliest months in aviation to date, in which 351 people were killed in six major accidents.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The **accessory drive** is a gearbox that forms part of a gas turbine engine.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Although not part of the engine's core, it drives the accessories – such as generators, pumps for fuel and lubrication oil, air compressors, hydraulic pumps and engine starters – that are otherwise essential for the operation of the engine or the aircraft on which it is mounted.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Accessory drives on large engines handle between 400–500 hp.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Power for the accessory drive is taken from the central shaft linking the turbine and compressor sections of the engine.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] This requires an internal gearbox that couples the drive to a radial driveshaft or *towershaft* that drives an external gearbox.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The design of the internal gearbox is complicated by the heat and small space available in which to connect the driveshaft.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] It is usually placed between the compressor outlet and the combustor.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] In turboprops or designs with centrifugal compressors, it may be placed ahead of the compressor.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] For two-shaft designs, an accessory drive will be taken from the high-pressure shaft, i.e. the outer and shorter of the two concentric shafts.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] This shaft comes up to speed more quickly when the engine is started.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The drive and accessory gearboxes may also be split in two, one driven from each engine shaft, so as to distribute their loads.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The engine-critical systems, including the starter drive, are arranged on the high-pressure shaft, with aircraft systems on the low-pressure shaft.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The high-pressure shaft also rotates faster than the low-pressure shaft, which may influence the distribution of accessories.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] To make the best use of the limited space for the driveshaft and internal gearbox, the driveshaft runs at high speed, thus allowing it to be of small diameter.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] This reduces the disruption to the airflow and the size of the hollow fairing that encloses it.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] If it is not possible to arrange a single straight path for the driveshaft, it may be arranged in two sections and linked by an intermediate gearbox.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] This is most commonly required for high-bypass turbofans with large diameter fans.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The packaging of an engine within its nacelle is a complicated task.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The accessory drive is usually arranged as a curved casing, so that the various accessories are mounted close to the engine.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The casing is a pair of light alloy castings.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Separate machined mounting pads are provided for each accessory.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The drive within the casing is provided by a train of spur gears.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Accessories are arranged on both sides of the driveshaft entry, in reducing order of their speed.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The gears are usually plain spur gears, running in roller bearings.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Idler gears are commonly used between them, to increase the spacing between accessories.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Helical gears are sometimes used for the high-torque drives, typically the starter, as these give smoother running.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] However helical gears also generate an end-thrust, which then requires a more complicated thrust bearing to support them.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] The complexity of an accessory drive and its gears is so great that they were used as a theme by the anthropomorphic illustrator Boris Artzybasheff in advertising for the Avco Lycoming company, who were making drive gearboxes for the Westinghouse J40 engine.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] In some engines, bleed air is also tapped to provide power for accessories, as well as a mechanical shaft drive.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Bleed air is particularly useful when a source of compressed air is specifically needed, either to pressurise cabin air, or as a supply of cooling air to other components (to avoid excess heat, this is taken for a low-pressure tapping, or from the LP compressor of a two-shaft engine).
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] One important use for bleed air is for cross-starting of other engines in a multi-engine aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Additional facilities are provided for a centrifugal oil breather, to separate the drive lubricating oil from the overboard breather air vent.
[src:glass-cockpit/accessory-drive] Also access for hand-turning the engine, during ground maintenance.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] An **adaptive compliant wing** is a wing which is flexible enough for aspects of its shape to be changed in flight.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible wings have a number of benefits.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Conventional flight control mechanisms operate using hinges, resulting in disruptions to the airflow, vortices, and in some cases, separation of the airflow.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] These effects contribute to the drag of the aircraft, resulting in less efficiency and higher fuel costs.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Flexible aerofoils can manipulate aerodynamic forces with less disruptions to the flow, resulting in less aerodynamic drag and improved fuel economy.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changing the shape of an aerodynamic surface has a direct effect on its aerodynamic properties.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] According to the flow condition and to the initial shape of the part, each shape variation (curvature, incidence, twist...) can have a different impact on the resulting forces and moments.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] This characteristic is actively pursued in adaptive wings which – by nature of their distributed compliance – can attain shape changes in a continuous, smooth, gap-free manner.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] By altering these geometrical parameters, the forces and moments can be modified, permitting to tailor them to the specific flight condition (e.g. for drag reduction) or to perform maneuvers (e.g. roll).
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Shape adaptation can be classified according to the motion it enables.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Changes of the airfoil shapes include altering its twist, and changing its camber and thickness distribution.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] An adaptive compliant wing designed by FlexSys Inc. features a variable-camber trailing edge which can be deflected up to ±10°, thus acting like a flap-equipped wing, but without the individual segments and gaps typical in a flap system.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing itself can be twisted up to 1° per foot of span.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The wing's shape can be changed at a rate of 30° per second, which is ideal for gust load alleviation.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The development of the adaptive compliant wing is being sponsored by the U.S.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Initially, the wing was tested in a wind tunnel, and then a 50-inch (1.3 m) section of wing was flight tested on board the Scaled Composites White Knight research aircraft in a seven-flight, 20-hour program operated from the Mojave Spaceport.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Adaptive compliant wings are also investigated at ETH Zurich in the frame of the Smart airfoil project.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The EU-funded Flexop program aims to develop to enable higher wing aspect ratio for less induced drag with lighter, more flexible airliner wings, along developing active flutter suppression for flexible wings.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] Partners include Hungary's MTA SZTAKI, Airbus, Austria's FACC, Inasco of Greece, Delft University of Technology, German aerospace center DLR, TUM, the UK's University of Bristol and RWTH Aachen University in Germany.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] On 19 November 2019, a 7 m (23 ft) span jet-powered UAV demonstrator with an aeroelastically tailored wing for passive load alleviation was flown in Oberpfaffenhofen, Germany, previously flown with a carbon-fiber, rigid wing to establish baseline performance.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] It has a conventional tube-and-wing configuration, unlike the blended wing body of the Lockheed Martin X-56.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] It follows the Grumman X-29 demonstrator in 1984, with more refined fiber orientations.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The flexible wing is 4% lighter than the rigid one.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The 54-month, €6.67 million ($7.4 million) project ends in November 2019, followed by the €3.85 million FLiPASED program from September 2019 until December 2022, using all the movable surfaces.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] The glass fiber flutter wing should to be flown in 2020, with unstable aeroelastic modes under 55 m/s (107 kn) that must be actively suppressed.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] With optimized aeroelastic tailoring and active flutter suppression, an aspect ratio of 12.4 could reduce fuel-burn by 5%, and 7% are targeted.
[src:glass-cockpit/adaptive-compliant-wing] FLiPASED is also led by MTA SZTAKI and include partners TUM, DLR and French aerospace research agency ONERA.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Modern aerodynamics only dates back to the seventeenth century, but aerodynamic forces have been harnessed by humans for thousands of years in sailboats and windmills, and images and stories of flight appear throughout recorded history including the Ancient Greek legend of Icarus and Daedalus.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Fundamental concepts of continuum, drag, and pressure gradients appear in the work of Aristotle and Archimedes.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In 1726, Sir Isaac Newton became the first person to develop a theory of air resistance, making him one of the first aerodynamicists.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Dutch-Swiss mathematician Daniel Bernoulli followed in 1738 with *Hydrodynamica* in which he described a fundamental relationship between pressure, density, and flow velocity for incompressible flow known today as Bernoulli's principle, which provides one method for calculating aerodynamic lift.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In 1757, Leonhard Euler published the more general Euler equations which could be applied to both compressible and incompressible flows.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The Euler equations were extended to incorporate the effects of viscosity in the first half of the 1800s, resulting in the Navier–Stokes equations.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The Navier–Stokes equations are the most general governing equations of fluid flow but are difficult to solve for the flow around all but the simplest of shapes.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In 1799, Sir George Cayley became the first person to identify the four aerodynamic forces of flight (weight, lift, drag, and thrust), as well as the relationships between them, and in doing so outlined the path toward achieving heavier-than-air flight for the next century.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In 1871, Francis Herbert Wenham constructed the first wind tunnel, allowing precise measurements of aerodynamic forces.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Drag theories were developed by Jean Le Rond d'Alembert, Gustav Kirchhoff, and Lord Rayleigh.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In 1889, Charles Renard, a French aeronautical engineer, became the first person to reasonably predict the power needed for sustained flight.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Otto Lilienthal, the first person to become highly successful with glider flights, was also the first to propose thin, curved airfoils that would produce high lift and low drag.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Building on these developments as well as research carried out in their own wind tunnel, the Wright brothers flew the first powered airplane on December 17, 1903.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] During the time of the first flights, Frederick W.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Lanchester, Martin Kutta, and Nikolai Zhukovsky independently created theories which connected circulation of a fluid flow to lift.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Kutta and Zhukovsky then developed a two-dimensional wing theory.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Expanding upon the work of Lanchester, Ludwig Prandtl is credited with developing the mathematics behind thin-airfoil and lifting-line theories as well as working with boundary layers.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] As aircraft speed increased designers began to encounter challenges associated with air compressibility at speeds near the speed of sound.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The differences in airflow under such conditions lead to problems in aircraft control, increased drag due to shock waves and the threat of structural failure due to aeroelastic flutter.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The ratio of the flow speed to the speed of sound was named the Mach number after Ernst Mach who was one of the first to investigate the properties of the supersonic flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Macquorn Rankine and Pierre Henri Hugoniot independently developed the theory for flow properties before and after a shock wave, while Jakob Ackeret led the initial work of calculating the lift and drag of supersonic airfoils.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Theodore von Kármán and Hugh Latimer Dryden introduced the term transonic to describe flow speeds between the critical Mach number and Mach 1 where drag increases rapidly.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The rapid increase in drag led aerodynamicists and aviators to disagree on whether supersonic flight was achievable until the sound barrier was broken in 1947 using the Bell X-1 aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] By the time the sound barrier was broken, aerodynamicists' understanding of the subsonic and low supersonic flow had matured.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The Cold War prompted the design of an ever-evolving line of high-performance aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Computational fluid dynamics began as an effort to solve for flow properties around complex objects and has rapidly grown to the point where entire aircraft can be designed using computer software, with wind-tunnel tests followed by flight tests to confirm the computer predictions.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Understanding of supersonic and hypersonic aerodynamics has matured since the 1960s, and the goals of aerodynamicists have shifted from the behaviour of fluid flow to the engineering of a vehicle such that it interacts predictably with the fluid flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Understanding the motion of air around an object (often called a flow field) enables the calculation of forces and moments acting on the object.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In many aerodynamics problems, the forces of interest are the fundamental forces of flight: lift, drag, thrust, and weight.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Of these, lift and drag are aerodynamic forces, i.e. forces due to air flow over a solid body.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Calculation of these quantities is often founded upon the assumption that the flow field behaves as a continuum.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Continuum flow fields are characterized by properties such as flow velocity, pressure, density, and temperature, which may be functions of position and time.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] These properties may be directly or indirectly measured in aerodynamics experiments or calculated starting with the equations for conservation of mass, momentum, and energy in air flows.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Density, flow velocity, and an additional property, viscosity, are used to classify flow fields.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Flow velocity is used to classify flows according to speed regime.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are flow fields in which the air speed field is always below the local speed of sound.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Transonic flows include both regions of subsonic flow and regions in which the local flow speed is greater than the local speed of sound.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Supersonic flows are defined to be flows in which the flow speed is greater than the speed of sound everywhere.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] A fourth classification, hypersonic flow, refers to flows where the flow speed is much greater than the speed of sound.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree on the precise definition of hypersonic flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Compressible flow accounts for varying density within the flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Subsonic flows are often idealized as incompressible, i.e. the density is assumed to be constant.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Transonic and supersonic flows are compressible, and calculations that neglect the changes of density in these flow fields will yield inaccurate results.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Viscosity is associated with the frictional forces in a flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In some flow fields, viscous effects are very small, and approximate solutions may safely neglect viscous effects.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] These approximations are called inviscid flows.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity is not neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Finally, aerodynamic problems may also be classified by the flow environment.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] External aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes (e.g. around an airplane wing), while internal aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages inside solid objects (e.g. through a jet engine).
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Unlike liquids and solids, gases are composed of discrete molecules which occupy only a small fraction of the volume filled by the gas.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] On a molecular level, flow fields are made up of the collisions of many individual gas molecules among themselves, and their collisions with solid surfaces.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] However, in most aerodynamics applications, the discrete molecular nature of gases is ignored, and the flow field is assumed to behave as a continuum.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] This assumption allows fluid properties such as density and flow velocity to be defined everywhere within the flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The validity of the continuum assumption is dependent on the density of the gas and the application in question.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] For the continuum assumption to be valid, the mean free path length must be much smaller than the length scale of the application in question.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] For example, many aerodynamics applications deal with aircraft flying in atmospheric conditions, where the mean free path length is on the order of micrometers and where the body is orders of magnitude larger.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In these cases, the length scale of the aircraft ranges from a few meters to a few tens of meters, which is much larger than the mean free path length.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] For such applications, the continuum assumption is reasonable.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The continuum assumption is less valid for extremely low-density flows like those encountered by vehicles at very high altitudes (e.g.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] 300,000 ft/90 km) or satellites in Low Earth orbit.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In these cases, statistical mechanics is a more accurate method of solving the problem than is continuum aerodynamics.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The Knudsen number can be used to guide the choice between statistical mechanics and the continuous formulation of aerodynamics.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The assumption of a fluid continuum allows problems in aerodynamics to be solved using fluid dynamics conservation laws.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Together, the equations are known as Navier–Stokes equations, although some authors define the term to only include the momentum equation(s).
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Navier–Stokes equations have no known analytical solution and are solved in modern aerodynamics using computational techniques.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Because computational methods using high speed computers were not historically available and the high computational cost of solving these complex equations now that they are available, simplifications of the Navier–Stokes equations have been and continue to be employed.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Euler equations are a set of similar conservation equations which neglect viscosity and may be used in cases where the effect of viscosity is expected to be small.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Further simplifications lead to Laplace's equation and potential flow theory.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Additionally, Bernoulli's equation is a solution in one dimension to both the momentum and energy conservation equations.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The ideal gas law or another such equation of state is often used in conjunction with these equations to form a determined system which allows the solution for the unknown variables.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems are classified by the flow environment or properties of the flow, including flow speed, compressibility, and viscosity.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] *External* aerodynamics is the study of flow around solid objects of various shapes.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Evaluating the lift and drag on an airplane or the shock waves that form in front of the nose of a rocket are examples of external aerodynamics.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] *Internal* aerodynamics is the study of flow through passages in solid objects.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] For instance, internal aerodynamics encompasses the study of the airflow through a jet engine or through an air conditioning pipe.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic problems can also be classified according to whether the flow speed is below, near or above the speed of sound.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamicists disagree over the precise definition of hypersonic flow; a rough definition considers flows with Mach numbers above 5 to be hypersonic.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The influence of viscosity on the flow dictates a third classification.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Some problems may encounter only very small viscous effects, in that case viscosity can be considered to be negligible.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The approximations to these problems are called inviscid flows.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Flows for which viscosity cannot be neglected are called viscous flows.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] An incompressible flow is a flow in which density is constant in both time and space.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Although all real fluids are compressible, a flow is often approximated as incompressible if the effect of the density changes cause only small changes to the calculated results.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] This is more likely to be true when the flow speeds are significantly lower than the speed of sound.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Effects of compressibility are more significant at speeds close to or above the speed of sound.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The Mach number is used to evaluate whether the incompressibility can be assumed, otherwise the effects of compressibility must be included.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Subsonic (or low-speed) aerodynamics describes fluid motion in flows which are much lower than the speed of sound everywhere in the flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] There are several branches of subsonic flow but one special case arises when the flow is inviscid, incompressible and irrotational.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] This case is called potential flow and allows the differential equations which describe the flow to be a simplified version of the equations of fluid dynamics, thus making available to the aerodynamicist a range of quick and easy solutions.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In solving a subsonic problem, one decision to be made by the aerodynamicist is whether to incorporate the effects of compressibility.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Compressibility is a description of the amount of change of density in the flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] When the effects of compressibility on the solution are small, the assumption that density is constant may be made.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The problem is then an incompressible low-speed aerodynamics problem.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] When the density is allowed to vary, the flow is called compressible.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In air, compressibility effects are usually ignored when the Mach number in the flow does not exceed 0.3 (about 335 feet (102 m) per second or 228 miles (366 km) per hour at 60 °F (16 °C)).
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Above Mach 0.3, the problem flow should be described using compressible aerodynamics.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] According to the theory of aerodynamics, a flow is considered to be compressible if the density changes along a streamline.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] This means that–unlike incompressible flow–changes in density are considered.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In general, this is the case where the Mach number in part or all of the flow exceeds 0.3.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The Mach 0.3 value is rather arbitrary, but it is used because gas flows with a Mach number below that value demonstrate changes in density of less than 5%.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Furthermore, that maximum 5% density change occurs at the stagnation point (the point on the object where flow speed is zero), while the density changes around the rest of the object will be significantly lower.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Transonic, supersonic, and hypersonic flows are all compressible flows.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The term Transonic refers to a range of flow velocities just below and above the local speed of sound (generally taken as Mach 0.8–1.2).
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] It is defined as the range of speeds between the critical Mach number, when some parts of the airflow over an aircraft become supersonic, and a higher speed, typically near Mach 1.2, when all of the airflow is supersonic.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Between these speeds, some of the airflow is supersonic, while some of the airflow is not supersonic.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Supersonic aerodynamic problems are those involving flow speeds greater than the speed of sound.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Calculating the lift on the Concorde during cruise can be an example of a supersonic aerodynamic problem.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Supersonic flow behaves very differently from subsonic flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Fluids react to differences in pressure; pressure changes are how a fluid is "told" to respond to its environment.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Therefore, since sound is in fact, an infinitesimal pressure difference propagating through a fluid, the speed of sound in that fluid can be considered the fastest speed that "information" can travel in the flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] This difference most obviously manifests itself in the case of a fluid striking an object.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In front of that object, the fluid builds up a stagnation pressure as impact with the object brings the moving fluid to rest.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In fluid traveling at subsonic speed, this pressure disturbance can propagate upstream, changing the flow pattern ahead of the object and giving the impression that the fluid "knows" the object is there by seemingly adjusting its movement and is flowing around it.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In a supersonic flow, however, the pressure disturbance cannot propagate upstream.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Thus, when the fluid finally reaches the object it strikes it and the fluid is forced to change its properties – temperature, density, pressure, and Mach number—in an extremely violent and irreversible fashion called a shock wave.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The presence of shock waves, along with the compressibility effects of high-flow velocity (see Reynolds number) fluids, is the central difference between the supersonic and subsonic aerodynamics regimes.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, hypersonic speeds are speeds that are highly supersonic.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In the 1970s, the term generally came to refer to speeds of Mach 5 (5 times the speed of sound) and above.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The hypersonic regime is a subset of the supersonic regime.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Hypersonic flow is characterized by high temperature flow behind a shock wave, viscous interaction, and chemical dissociation of gas.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The incompressible and compressible flow regimes produce many associated phenomena, such as boundary layers and turbulence.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The concept of a boundary layer is important in many problems in aerodynamics.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The viscosity and fluid friction in the air is approximated as being significant only in this thin layer.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] This assumption makes the description of such aerodynamics much more tractable mathematically.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] In aerodynamics, turbulence is characterized by chaotic property changes in the flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] These include low momentum diffusion, high momentum convection, and rapid variation of pressure and flow velocity in space and time.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Flow that is not turbulent is called laminar flow.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is a significant element of vehicle design, including road cars and trucks where the main goal is to reduce the vehicle drag coefficient, and racing cars, where in addition to reducing drag the goal is also to increase the overall level of downforce.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamics is also important in the prediction of forces and moments acting on sailing vessels.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] It is used in the design of mechanical components such as hard drive heads.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Structural engineers resort to aerodynamics, and particularly aeroelasticity, when calculating wind loads in the design of large buildings, bridges, and wind turbines.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The aerodynamics of internal passages is important in heating/ventilation, gas piping, and in automotive engines where detailed flow patterns strongly affect the performance of the engine.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Urban aerodynamics are studied by town planners and designers seeking to improve amenity in outdoor spaces, or in creating urban microclimates to reduce the effects of urban pollution.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] The field of environmental aerodynamics describes ways in which atmospheric circulation and flight mechanics affect ecosystems.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Aerodynamic equations are used in numerical weather prediction.
[src:glass-cockpit/aerodynamics] Sports in which aerodynamics are of crucial importance include soccer, table tennis, cricket, baseball, and golf, in which most players can control the trajectory of the ball using the "Magnus effect".
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The CDS software is constituted of a kernel which is able to create the GUI hierarchy specified in the DF during initialization, thus not needing to be recompiled if the GUI definition changes.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The first version of ARINC 661 was adopted in 2001 as part of the ARINC standards.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Its first use was for Airbus A380 CDS development.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The first supplement was adopted in 2003, and added new widgets.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The second supplement was adopted in June 2005, and added supplementary widgets.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Third supplement has been adopted in 2007.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The standard is known today to be used for Airbus A380 and A400M CDS development, and also Boeing 787 CDS development.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] AgustaWestland company use VAPS XT ARINC 661 for the development of a new Touchscreen unit in the upgraded Merlin helicopter for the Royal Navy.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] In March 2011, Embraer announced that it selected SCADE Solutions for ARINC 661, a COTS (Commercial Off The Shelf) tool for ARINC 661 development, for its future developments.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] In February 2021, Boeing selected VAPS XT to support its Future Avionics User Interface Development Needs.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] An ARINC 661 Part 2 is currently in development, allowing to specify look and feel for widgets.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] In order to be compliant with the standard, a CDS must have a kernel that can create the widgets tree during CDS initialization, using the Definition File, and communicate with UA in both ways using the runtime protocol.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] ARINC 661 does not imply the use of a particular Data bus structure to perform the low-level communication between CDS and UA.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] For example, an ARINC 429 or Ethernet protocol such as ARINC 664 can be used, but it is not mandatory.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Each DF binary file specifies the GUI definition for one User Application (UA) User interface.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Several UA user interface trees can be combined to constitute the CDS display definition.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] A DF is composed of two parts : an optional symbol definition, and a widgets definition.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The widget library is similar to Widgets used in computing.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] There are Containers, Lists, ScrollPanes, Buttons, Menus, Labels, EditBoxes, etc...
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Although the DF File is binary, the standard has also defined an associated XML definition, which is easier to manipulate in tools.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The concepts used by ARINC 661 are close to those used in user interface markup languages, except that the UI language is binary and not XML-based.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The following example presents the XML Definition File for a Layer containing a panel enclosing a label, which shows the text "Hello World!".
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Note that contrary to most widget toolkits, ARINC 661 widgets origins are relative to the lower left-hand corner of their parent container, and screen units are not in pixel but in 1/100 of millimeters.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] COTS specification tools for DF specification currently include PACE VAPS XT 661 Toolkit, SCADE Solutions for ARINC 661 Compliant Systems, and DiSTI's GL Studio ARINC 661 Toolkit.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] PACE (at the time PRESAGIS) introduced the first COTS ARINC 661 development tool which allows creation of Widgets, Layers, DF Generation and deployment on embedded real-time operating systems (RTOS).
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] VAPS XT supports DO-178B/C certification up to DAL-A (Design Assurance Level).
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Because of the burden of Avionics software certification, the kernel must be embedded in a DO-178-compliant environment.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Flexible Software Solutions introduced COTS developing, testing and analysis tools for ARINC 661 protocol at the beginning of 2012.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The UA Accelerator software tool is used to develop ARINC 661 user applications while the UA Emulator software tool is used to test and debug UA and CDS ARINC 661 messaging.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] Ansys (at the time Esterel Technologies) announced on October 13, 2010, the availability of SCADE Solutions for ARINC 661 in 2011.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] SCADE Solutions for ARINC 661 allow creating both ARINC 661-compliant CDS and UA.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] For CDS developers, the toolchain features a complete customizable ARINC 661 compliant model-based widgets library and the automated generation of a portable ARINC 661 server, compliant with the DO-178B/DO-178C safety objectives up to level A.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] For UA developers, the toolchain features the model-based design and generation of DFs and the automatic generation of communication code between SCADE Suite UA models and the ARINC 661 Server.
[src:glass-cockpit/arinc-661] The GL Studio ARINC 661 Toolkit is a plug-in to GL Studio HMI Toolkit that delivers a set of pre-existing customizable widgets, a DF Generator, CDS, Communication Libraries, and a User Application Generator.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The **ATR 42** is a regional airliner produced by Franco-Italian manufacturer ATR, with final assembly in Toulouse, France.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 4 November 1981, the aircraft was launched with ATR, as a joint venture between French Aérospatiale (now part of Airbus) and Aeritalia (now Leonardo S.p.A.).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42-300 performed its maiden flight on 16 August 1984 and type certification was granted during September 1985.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Launch customer Air Littoral operated its first revenue-earning flight in December of that year.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The high-wing airliner is powered by two turboprop engines, Pratt & Whitney Canada PW120s.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The number "42" in its name is derived from the aircraft's original standard seating capacity of 42 passengers.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Later variants are upgraded with new avionics, a glass cockpit, and newer engine versions.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42 is the basis for the stretched ATR 72, introduced in October 1989.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During the 1960s and 1970s, European aircraft manufacturers had, for the most part, undergone considerable corporate restructuring, including mergers and consolidations, as well as moving towards collaborative multinational programmes, such as the newly launched Airbus A300.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] In line with this trend towards intra-European co-operation, French aerospace manufacturer Aérospatiale and Italian aviation conglomerate Aeritalia commenced discussions on the topic of working together to develop an all-new regional airliner.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Prior to this, both companies had been independently conducting studies for their own aircraft concepts, the AS 35 design in the case of Aerospatiale and the AIT 230 for Aeritalia, to conform with demand within this sector of the market as early as 1978.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 4 November 1981, a formal co-operation agreement was signed by Aeritalia chairman Renato Bonifacio and Aerospatiale chairman Jacques Mitterrand in Paris.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] This agreement signaled not only the merger of their efforts, but also of their separate concept designs together into a single complete aircraft design for the purpose of pursuing its development and manufacture as a collaborative joint venture.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The consortium then targeted a similar unit cost, but a 430 kg (950 lb) fuel consumption over a 200 nmi (370 km; 230 mi) sector, nearly half the 790 kg (1,750 lb) required by its 40–50 seat competitors, the British Aerospace HS.748 and Fokker F.27, and planned a 58-seat ATR XX stretch.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] This agreement served not only as the basis and origins of the ATR company, but also as the effective launch point of what would become the fledgling firm's first aircraft, which was designated as the ATR 42.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] By 1983, ATR's customer services division has been set up, readying infrastructure worldwide to provide support for ATR's upcoming aircraft to any customer regardless of location.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 16 August 1984, the first ATR 42 conducted its maiden flight from Toulouse Airport, France.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During September 1985, both the French Directorate General for Civil Aviation (DGCA) and the Italian Italian Civil Aviation Authority awarded type certification for the type, clearing it to commence operational service.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 3 December 1985, the first production aircraft, designated as the ATR 42-300, was delivered to French launch customer Air Littoral, with the first revenue service, between Béziers Cap d'Agde Airport and Paris Orly airport taking place on 23 December.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During January 1986, already confident of the ATR 42's success and of the demand for an enlarged version of the aircraft, ATR announced that the launch of a programme to develop such an aircraft, which was designated as the ATR 72 to reflect its increased passenger capacity.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] By the end of 1986, the ATR 42 had accumulated a sizable backlog of orders, which in turn led to a ramping up of the type's rate of production.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During August 1988, ATR's marketing efforts in the lucrative North American market resulted in the securing of a large order of 50 ATR-42-300s from US operator Texas Air Corporation; that same year, another American regional carrier, Trans World Express, received the 100th production aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 1 July 1989, ATR opened their new global training centre for the type in Toulouse, which provided centralised and modern facilities for the training to airline staff and other personnel across the world.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During June 1999, the ATR global training center became one of the first European institutions to be recognised as a Type Rating Training Organization, as defined by the Joint Aviation Authorities.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During September 1989, ATR announced it had achieved its original target of 400 sales of the ATR.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] That same year, deliveries of the enlarged ATR 72 commenced; shortly thereafter, both types commonly were ordered together.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Since the smaller ATR 42 is assembled on the same production line as the ATR 72, along with sharing the majority of subsystems, components, and manufacturing techniques, the two types support each other to remain in production.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] This factor may have been crucial, as by 2015, the ATR 42 was the only 50-seat regional aircraft that was still being manufactured.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] To maintain a technological edge on the highly competitive market for regional airliners during the 1990s, several modifications and improved versions of the ATR 42 were progressively introduced.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The initial ATR 42-300 model remained in production until 1996, while the first upgraded (and broadly similar) model, designated as the 'ATR 42-320, was also produced until 1996.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The -320 variant principally differed in that it was powered by a pair of the more-powerful PW121 engines, giving it improved performance over the 300.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Another variant, the ATR 42-300QC, was a dedicated quick-change (convertible) freight/passenger version of the standard -300 series.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The next major production version was the ATR 42-500 series, the development of which having been originally announced on 14 June 1993.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 31 October 1995, the first ATR 42-500 was delivered to Italian operator Air Dolomiti; on 19 January 1996, the first revenue service to be performed by the type was conducted.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 19 November 2000, 120 min ETOPS were approved.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] In addition to new aircraft models, various organisational changes were also implemented.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 10 July 1998, ATR launched its new asset management department.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] In June 2001, EADS and Alenia Aeronautica, ATR's parent companies, decided to reinforce their partnership, regrouping all industrial activities related to regional airliners underneath the ATR consortium.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 3 October 2003, ATR became one of the first aircraft manufacturers to be certified under ISO 9001-2000 and EN/AS/JISQ 9100, the worldwide quality standard for the aeronautics industry.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During July 2004, ATR and Brazilian aircraft manufacturer Embraer announced a cooperation agreement on the AEROChain Portal for the purpose of delivering improved customer service.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During April 2009, ATR announced the launch of its 'Door-2-Door' service as a new option in its comprehensive customer-services range.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The current production version is the ATR 42-600 series.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 2 October 2007, ATR CEO Stéphane Mayer announced the launch of the -600 series aircraft; the ATR 42-600 and ATR 72-600 featured various improvements to increase efficiency, dispatch reliability, and lower fuel burn and operating costs.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] While broadly similar to the earlier -500 model, differences include the adoption of improved PW127M engines, a new glass cockpit, and a variety of other minor improvements.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Using the test registration *F-WWLY*, the prototype ATR 42-600 first flew on 4 March 2010.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The first aircraft was delivered to Tanzanian airline Precision Air in November 2012.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Speaking in October 2015, ATR CEO Patrick de Castelbajac stated that the firm was set to produce in excess of 90 aircraft that year, and that the new manufacturing facilities could support a production rate of up to 120 per year.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] At the time, the company had a backlog of orders for 300 aircraft, sufficient for three years' of production.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During 2017, a new in-house financing and leasing division was established by ATR to offer customers a greater degree of support and expand the company's range of services.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Considerable emphasis has been placed upon the continuous development of ATR's aircraft models.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It could introduce a steep approach capability and operating costs that compare to 30-seaters.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] STOL improvements should be launched in 2019 to reduce landing distance from 1,100 to 800 m (3,600 to 2,600 ft).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] ATR estimates a market for STOL 20–42 seaters of 800 over 30 years, to serve islands and deliver cargo to short runways.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42-600S empty weight will be reduced with lighter seats and galley fittings.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The variant was officially announced at the June 2019 Paris Air Show.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Irish lessor Elix Aviation Capital will be the launch customer, taking 10 aircraft from 2022 to 2024; commitments from Air Tahiti and another undisclosed customer bring the total order book to 17.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 9 October 2019, ATR launched the ATR 42-600S at the European Regions Airline Association General Assembly, with 20 commitments including from Elix Aviation Capital (10 aircraft) and Air Tahiti (two aircraft).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Capable of operating from 800 m (2,600 ft) runways with up to 42 passengers, certification is expected for the second half of 2022 before first delivery.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42-600S can access close to 500 airports with an 800–1,000 m (2,600–3,300 ft) runway, expanding its addressable market by 25%.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] 800 m runway operation is limited to 200 nmi (370 km; 230 mi) long flights with 70% used seats.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The variant made a 2h 15min maiden flight on 11 May 2022, while the larger rudder will be fitted at the end of 2022 before the certification phase start in 2023.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] In November 2024 ATR terminated the development of the 42-600S STOL version, opting instead to focus on improving the efficiency of the entire ATR 42 and ATR 72 families.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42 is a straight high-wing airliner with twin turboprops and a T-tail, certified in the transport category, and powered by Pratt & Whitney Canada PW120s.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It has deicing boots to fly in icing conditions and a retractable landing gear in fairings under the fuselage, with wheel sides visible in flight.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It has no Auxiliary Power Unit (APU), but can still be autonomous in ground operations, as it has a propeller brake on the starboard engine, allowing the engine to remain running to provide power on the ground.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It has a pressurized cabin with a circular cross-section, with a 2.57 m (8 ft 5 in) inside width for four-abreast seating, allowing 48 seats at a 30 in (760 mm) seat pitch.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It has a 54.5 m2 (587 sq ft) wing area and a 24.57 m (80.6 ft) wing span, for a 11.1 wing aspect ratio.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It can reach a cruise speed of 300 kn (560 km/h) true air speed, with a fuel flow of 811 kg/h (1,788 lb/h): a fuel economy of 1.46 kg/km (5.96 lb/nmi) or 3.8 L/100 km (62 mpg‑US) per seat with 48 seats and a jet fuel density of 0.8.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 21 August 1990, US airline American Eagle placed a large order for ATRs, composed of 41 ATR 42s and 59 ATR 72s, further consolidating ATR's position in North America.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 5 September 1997, American Eagle took delivery of the 500th ATR to be built.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 5 June 1998, Tarom, the national carrier of Romania, accepted delivery of its first two ATR 42-500s, of a batch of seven aircraft ordered a year earlier.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 28 June 1998, ATR gained a foothold in the Cuban market following an order from airline Cubana de Aviacion for the ATR 42.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During 2000, the combined global ATR fleet attained its 10,000,000th flight, during which a cumulative distance around 4 billion km (2.5 billion statute miles) had been traversed, and around 450 million passengers had flown onboard ATR-built aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] In 2007, a new record was set for the programme's sales; 113 new ATR aircraft having been ordered during a single year.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] 2011 was another record-breaking year for sales at ATR.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] According to ATR's CEO Filippo Bagnato, sales had continued to grow during the Great Recession despite the downturn experienced by most aviation companies as "fuel consumption that can be half that of the alternatives and [with] lower maintenance costs".
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] For 2013, ATR claimed a 48% global market share for regional aircraft deliveries between 50 and 90 seats (comprising both turboprops and jets), making it the dominant manufacturer within this sector of the market.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] That same year, during which firm orders for 10 ATR 42-600s and 79 ATR 72-600s were recorded, leasing companies were responsible for 70% of these; according to ATR's CEO Filippo Bagnato: "Years ago, we were not even considered by the lessors; now they see ATRs as a good investment".
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During May 1997, ATR had achieved its first breakthrough sale in China, placed by operator China Xinjiang Airlines and the CAAC.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During late 2014, ATR set up a new office in Beijing, and hired several former Airbus sales personnel with the aim of launching the type on the Chinese market.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] ATR believed that many of the already-flown routes did not suit larger 150-seat aircraft; however, of the roughly 2,600 commercial aircraft flying in China at that time, only 68 had a capacity less than 90 seats and of these, fewer than 20 aircraft were powered by turboprop engines.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During January 2017, Japanese regional airliner Japan Air Commuter (JAC) has taken delivery of its first ATR 42-600, becoming the first owner-operator of the type in the nation.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The aircraft was one of nine to have been ordered by JAC, along with options for a further 14 ATR 42s, as a replacement for its aging Saab 340 fleet; reportedly, JAC is considering replacing its Bombardier Q400s with ATRs, as well.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Silver Airways started to operate the ATR 42-600 on 22 April 2019, making it the first airline to fly the -600 variant in the USA.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The carrier has 16 firm orders for ATR turboprops with options to purchase 30 additional aircraft from ATR through lessor Nordic Aviation Capital.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] In September 2024, Nepalese airline Buddha Air became the first to retire their ATR 42-320 by completing its economic life cycle of 70000 cycles.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The -200 was the original ATR 42 prototype, and only a few were built for testing purposes.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It was powered by Pratt & Whitney Canada PW120 engines rated at 1,800 shp (1,300 kW).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The -300 was the standard production version.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It was powered by Pratt & Whitney Canada PW120 engines rated at 2,000 shp (1,500 kW).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The -320 was an improved version of the -300 powered by PW121 engines (2100 shp).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It was designed to have better performance, especially in hot and high conditions.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42-400 is an upgraded version of the -320 using six-bladed propellers on otherwise identical PW121 engines and small mini winglets on the edge of the wings.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Three ATR 42-400s were delivered to the government of Italy as the ATR 42 "Surveyor" version.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The only two civilian ATR 42-400s produced (msn 487 and 491) were delivered to CSA Czech Airlines in 1995/1996 as an interim upgrade prior to delivery of -500s.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] In 2006, these two aircraft were sold to Conviasa.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42-500 is a further upgraded version, the first delivery of which occurring during October 1995.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It has many improvements for performance and passenger comfort, including new engines, new propellers, a newly designed cabin, and increased weight.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It has six-bladed propellers powered by PW127E engines rated at 2,400 shp (1,800 kW) for improved hot and high performance and increased cruise speed.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Propellers are electrically controlled and are made from composite.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It has an increased maximum takeoff weight, allowing for more cargo and greater range.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Due to the six-bladed propellers and better insulation, it has reduced noise levels.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The newest version has CATII capability and dual Honeywell HT1000 FMS installation.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] During October 2007, the launch of the ATR 42-600 series was announced.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Akin to the ATR 72-500, the -600 series featured the PW127M as its standard engine (providing 5% additional thrust, thus improving performance on short runways, in hot weather, and at high altitude); the "boost function" activates the additional power as needed.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It also features a glass cockpit flight deck, complete with five wide LCD screens, that replaced the previous electronic flight instrument system; additionally, a multipurpose computer enhances flight safety and operational capabilities.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Avionics supplied by Thales provides CAT III and required navigation performance capabilities.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] It also includes lighter, more comfortable seats and larger overhead baggage bins.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] According to the third issue of its EASA's Type Certificate, ATR 42-600 is ATR's marketing designation for the -500 series when fitted with the new avionics suite) or "glass Cockpit".
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42-600 designation is not recognised by EASA as a certified aircraft model or variant, and is not used on ATR certified/approved documentation; instead, only "Mod 5948", "ATR 42-500 with Mod 5948", "ATR 42-500 fitted with NAS", or "ATR 42-500 600 version" is used.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42-600S was the STOL (short takeoff and landing) variant of the -600.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The aircraft was planned to be capable of operating from runways as short as 800-metre-long (2,600 ft) with up to 34 passengers, and 890-metre-long (2,920 ft) fully seated (48 passengers) on short routes.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] ATR launched the ATR 42-600S at the ERA General Assembly, with 20 commitments including from Elix Aviation Capital (10 aircraft) and Air Tahiti (two aircraft).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Certification was expected for the second half of 2022 before first delivery.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] In November 2024 ATR decided to halt development of the 42-600S, due to "a reduced addressable market compared to the initial forecast".
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42-600 and ATR 42-600S HighLine had an executive cabin layout, otherwise it is the same as its original counterpart.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] Bulk (tube versions) and ULD freighter (large cargo door).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] An STC exists to convert all ATR-42 variants to all-cargo transport aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] FedEx, UPS, and DHL are major operators of the type.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR-42 "Surveyor" is a maritime patrol version of the -400.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] VIP transport and in-flight inspection versions of the -500 also exist.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] On 1 August 2017, Silver Airways placed orders for 20 ATR 42-600 aircraft, marking the entry of the -600 into the U.S. market, with four in service as of fourth quarter 2019.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] By November 2018, Loganair was to replace its Saab 340s and Saab 2000s, costly to operate and maintain, mostly the 2000, with around 20 ATR 42s over four to five years from the third quarter of 2019.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] As of August 2022, 6 ATR 42s were in military service.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-42] The ATR 42 has been involved in 47 aviation accidents and incidents including 34 hull losses.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The **ATR 72** is a twin-engine turboprop, short-haul regional airliner developed and produced in France and Italy by aircraft manufacturer ATR.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The number "72" in its name is derived from the aircraft's typical standard seating capacity of 72 passengers.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The ATR 72 has also been used as a corporate transport, cargo aircraft, and maritime patrol aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] To date, all of the ATR series have been completed at the company's final assembly line in Toulouse, France; ATR benefits from sharing resources and technology with Airbus SE, which has continued to hold a 50% interest in the company.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Successive models of the ATR 72 have been developed.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Typical updates have included new avionics, such as a glass cockpit, and the adoption of newer engine versions to deliver enhanced performance, such as increased efficiency and reliability and reductions in operating costs.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The aircraft shares a high degree of commonality with the smaller ATR 42, which remains in production as of 2025.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] ATR (French: *Avions de transport régional* or Italian: *Aerei da Trasporto Regionale*) is a joint venture formed by French aerospace company Aérospatiale (now part of Airbus) and Italian aviation conglomerate Aeritalia (now Leonardo S.p.A.).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During the 1980s, French aerospace company Aérospatiale and Italian aviation conglomerate Aeritalia merged their work on a new generation of regional aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The new jointly owned company, ATR, was established to develop, manufacture, and market their first airliner, later designated the ATR 42.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] On 16 August 1984, the first model of the series, designated as the ATR 42-300, performed the type's maiden flight.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During the mid-1980s, the ATR 72 was developed as a stretched variant of the ATR 42.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] On 27 October 1989, Finnish airline Finnair became the first airline to operate this type in revenue service.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During the mid-1980s, ATR sought to introduce a larger airliner with increased capacity over its earlier products.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] This new regional airliner, designated as the ATR 72, was directly developed from the earlier ATR 42 and had much in common with it; the principal difference between the two airliners was an increase in the maximum seating capacity from 48 to 78 passengers.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] This was principally achieved by stretching the fuselage by 4.5 m (15 ft), along with an increase of the wingspan, the use of more powerful engines, and increased fuel capacity by about 10%.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] On 15 January 1986, the launch of the stretched ATR 72 programme was announced.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] On 27 October 1988, the prototype performed its maiden flight.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] One year later, on 25 September 1989, the ATR 72 received airworthiness certification from the French Directorate General for Civil Aviation.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The following month, on 27 October 1989, Finnish airline Finnair became the first to introduce the aircraft into service.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Since the ATR 72 is assembled on the same production line as the smaller ATR 42, along with sharing the majority of subsystems, components, and manufacturing techniques, the two types support each other to remain in production.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] This factor may have been crucial as, by 2015, the ATR 42 was the only 50-seat regional aircraft still being manufactured.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] In 2000, the combined global ATR fleet reached its 10,000,000th flight, during which a distance of around 4 billion km (2.5 billion statute miles) and around 450 million passengers had flown on board ATR-built aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The 2007 production set a new record for the programme's sales; a total of 113 new ATR aircraft had been ordered during a single year.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] By the end of 2014, ATR had received 1,000 orders for the type and delivered 754, leaving a backlog of 246 aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Various organisational changes were implemented within the ATR company.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] In June 2001, EADS and Alenia Aeronautica, ATR's parent companies, decided to reinforce their partnership, regrouping all industrial activities related to regional airliners into the ATR consortium.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] On 3 October 2003, ATR became one of the first aircraft manufacturers to be certified under ISO 9000-2000 and EN/AS/JISQ 9100, the worldwide quality standard for the aeronautics industry.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During July 2004, ATR and Brazilian aircraft manufacturer Embraer announced a co-operation agreement on the AEROChain Portal to deliver improved customer service.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During April 2009, ATR announced the launch of its 'Door-2-Door' service as a new option in its comprehensive customer services range.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] As of October 2007, the current production version is the *ATR 72-600* series.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] On 2 October 2007, ATR CEO Stéphane Mayer announced the launch of the -600 series aircraft; the ATR 42-600 and ATR 72-600 featured various improvements to increase efficiency, dispatch reliability, lower fuel burn, and operating costs.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] While broadly similar to the earlier -500 model, differences include adopting improved PW127M engines, a new glass cockpit, and various other minor improvements.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Since 2008, ATR has been a participant in the European Clean Sky Joint Technology Initiative.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] ATR's senior vice-president for engineering Alessandro Amendola indicated that the elimination of all uses of bleed air was a key aim in the designing of an all-electric architecture as well as improving engine efficiency; the minimising of peak electrical loads was also a stated priority.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During March 2016, a second round of flight trials dedicated the testing of all-electric systems architecture using the demonstrator was completed; analysis is set to continue.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] At the time, the company had a backlog of orders for 300 aircraft, sufficient for three years of production.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During 2017, a new in-house financing and leasing division was established by ATR in order to offer customers a greater degree of support and expand the company's range of services.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] In December 2015, the EASA approved a new high-density seating layout, raising the maximum capacity from 74 to 78 seats.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During the 2021 Dubai Airshow in mid-November 2021, ATR debuted the new ATR 72-600 powered by new PW127XT powerplants with 20% lower maintenance cost and 3% lower fuel consumption than the predecessor PW127M powerplant.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Speaking at the Farnborough Airshow in July 2016, the CEO of ATR Patrick de Castelbajac stated that the company was currently examining the possibility of replacing the current Pratt & Whitney Canada PW127 engine with either a new offer from P&WC, or a GE38 derivative from GE Aviation.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Although expressing satisfaction with the PW127 engine and its supplier, Castelbajac noted the design's age and the need to remain competitive with the latest regional jets.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] To be a worthwhile exercise, any re-engine exercise would require a 15 per cent improvement in fuel-burn and 20-25 per cent reduction of direct maintenance costs.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Additionally, Castelbajac sees the potential re-engine as a "bridge" to the eventual development of a larger 100-seat aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] However, in January 2018, ATR's parent company Leonardo announced that the 100-seat program has been formally brought to a close.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The ATR 72 is a turboprop-powered regional airliner, capable of accommodating a maximum of 78 passengers.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] It is powered by a pair of Pratt & Whitney Canada PW100 turboprop engines, which drive an arrangement of four or six-bladed propellers supplied by Hamilton Standard.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Earlier models of the ATR 72 are equipped with the older PW124B engine, rated at 1,800 kilowatts (2,400 shp), while later-built aircraft are powered by the newer PW127 engine, rated at a maximum of 2,050 kW (2,750 shp) to achieve improved "hot and high" takeoff performance.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] It can land and takeoff in high airports with short runways like Andorra Airport.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] It employs carbonfibres for 30% of the wing by weight, for a 20% weight reduction.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] In a standard configuration, the aircraft does not have an auxiliary power unit; when present it is installed within the C4 cargo section.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Most operators of the ATR 72 equip their aircraft with a propeller brake that stops the propeller on the No.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] 2 (right) engine while allowing the turbine to continue running, to provide both airflow and electrical power to the aircraft while on the ground.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] While passengers are boarding or disembarking, a tail stand is set into place as standard procedure to guard against the aircraft nose lifting off the ground.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] 2011 was a record-breaking year for sales at ATR.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] For 2013, ATR claimed a 48 percent global market share for regional aircraft deliveries between 50 and 90 seats (comprising both turboprops and jets), making it the dominant manufacturer in this market segment.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] That same year, during which firm orders for 10 ATR 42-600s and 79 ATR 72-600s were recorded, leasing companies were responsible for 70 per cent of these; according to ATR's CEO Filippo Bagnato: "Years ago, we were not even considered by the lessors; now they see ATRs as a good investment".
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Placing their first order during 2011, by December 2012, Singaporean lessor Avation had a combined total of 20 ATR 72s on order; by February 2016, the number on order for Avation had risen to 35 aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During May 1997, ATR achieved their first breakthrough sale in China, placed by operator China Xinjiang Airlines and the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During late 2014, ATR set up a new office in Beijing and hired several former Airbus sales personnel with the aim of launching the type in the Chinese market.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] ATR believed that many of the already-flown routes did not suit larger 150-seat aircraft; however, of the roughly 2,600 commercial aircraft flying in China at that time, only 68 had a capacity of less than 90 seats and of these, fewer than 20 were powered by turboprop engines.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During February 2016, ATR signed a deal with flag carrier Iran Air for a batch of 20 ATR 72-600s, along with options for 20 more aircraft and post-purchase services, such as engine maintenance.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Made possible by a negotiated relaxation of international sanctions against Iran, during June 2017, a €1 billion Iranian contract was finalized for the firm 20 airliners and 20 options; the delivery of the first four aircraft occurred within weeks of the deal being completed.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] US sanctions against Iran were reimposed in August 2018, by which time 13 of the order of 20 aircraft had been delivered.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] In April 2019 the US Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) issued a two-year licence to ATR to allow it to supply spare parts and other essentials to keep the fleet of 13 ATR 72-600s in operation.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] However, the remaining 7 ATR 72-600s from the 2016 order remain sanctioned and in storage.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] While primarily used as a civil aircraft, some ATR 72s have been adapted to perform in various military functions, such as utility aircraft and maritime patrol aircraft (MPA).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The Turkish Navy, which initially decided to purchase ten ATR 72-500 MPA, later changed its order to eight aircraft: Two ATR 72-600 TMUA (Turkish Maritime Utility Aircraft) versions, and six ATR 72-600 TMPA (Turkish Maritime Patrol Aircraft for MP/ASW/ASuW duties) versions.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The armed ATR 72 TMPA variant was developed in cooperation with Turkish Aerospace Industries (TAI), and incorporated additional sensors and mission systems to perform its intended combat role.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During 2013, the two ATR 72-600 TMUA aircraft were delivered to the Turkish Navy.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The first ATR 72-600 TMPA was delivered in December 2020 and the second one in March 2021 was already in service with Turkish Navy.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] As of May 2021, 3 ATR 72-600 TMUA aircraft are being operated by the Turkish Navy.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The Italian Air Force selected the ATR 72-600 MP, designated as the *P-72A*, to serve as a multirole maritime patrol, electronic surveillance and C4 platform.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The original Italian requirement for a Breguet Atlantic replacement had also called for ASW and anti-surface warfare (ASuW) capabilities, however, during 2014, the contract was renegotiated to a configuration that excluded these capabilities.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] An anticipated variant for ASW and ASuW operations may later be pursued; accordingly, provisions were made to allow for the four P-72As on order to be adapted to the ASW configuration.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] In December 2016, the first pair of P-72A aircraft were delivered to the Italian Air Force.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The last aircraft was delivered to the Italian Air Force in February 2021.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] A single ATR 72 MP was ordered by Italy's paramilitary Guardia di Finanza (GdF) in July 2019, followed by an order for a further three ATR 72s in October 2019.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The aircraft, called P-72B by Guardia di Finanza, will supplement the GdF's existing force of four ATR-42s in the border surveillance, maritime patrol and search and rescue roles.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] On 8 November 2017, FedEx Express launched the -600 cargo variant with 30 firm orders plus 20 options, in a freighter configuration from the factory.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] As of September 2018, 187 early variants had been produced with 172 operated by 55 carriers, 365 -500s were delivered with more than 350 in service at 75 operators, 444 -600s were produced and are operated by 74 carriers with a backlog of 231 orders.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] By then, with more than 60 -500s and 40 -600s in storage, new aircraft leases fell to $130,000 per month from $170,000.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The ATR 72 was a candidate to replace the German Navy's P-3, at least as a stopgap solution from 2025 to 2032.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Germany ultimately selected the P-8A Poseidon in 2021.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Two subtypes were marketed as the 100 series (-100).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Initial production variant with front and rear passenger doors, powered by two PW124B engines and certified in September 1989.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Initial production variant with a front cargo door and a rear passenger door, powered by two PW124B engines and certified in December 1989.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Two sub-types were marketed as the 200 series (-200).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The -200 was the original production version, powered by Pratt & Whitney Canada PW124B engines rated at 2,400 shp (1,800 kW).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Higher maximum take-off weight variant of the -101, a PW124B-powered variant certified in September 1989.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Higher maximum take-off weight variant of the -102, a PW124B-powered variant certified in December 1989.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Two subtypes were marketed as the 210 series (-210): the -211 (and with an enlarged cargo door, called the -212) is a -200 with PW127 engines producing 2,750 shp (2,050 kW) each for improved performance in hot and high-altitude conditions.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The subtypes differ in the type of doors and emergency exits.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] PW127-powered variant certified in December 1992.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Certified in January 1997 and fitted with either PW127F or PW127M engines, the -212A is an upgraded version of the -210 using six-bladed propellers on otherwise identical PW127F engines.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Other improvements include higher maximum weights and superior performance, as well as greater automation of power management to ease pilot workload.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Initial marketing name for the ATR 72-212A.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Marketing name for ATR 72-212A with different equipment fit.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The -600 series aircraft was announced in October 2007; the first deliveries were planned for the second half of 2010.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The prototype ATR 72-600 first flew on 24 July 2009; it had been converted from an ATR 72-500.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The ATR 72-600 features several improvements.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] engines, which enable a 5% increase in takeoff power via a "boost function" used only when called for by takeoff conditions.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] It also features lighter seats and larger overhead baggage bins.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During the 2021 Dubai Airshow in mid-November 2021, ATR debuted the new ATR 72-600 engine which is powered by new PW127XT powerplants with 20% lower maintenance cost and 3% lower fuel consumption than the predecessor PW127M powerplant.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The ATR 72-600 HighLine is the same as the ATR 72-600 however it featured an executive cabin layout.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The ATR 72MP is an ATR 72-600 derivative developed by Leonardo for search and rescue, maritime patrol, command and control, communication, computers, intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance (C4ISR).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Leonardo Electronics designed its *Airborne Tactical Observation and Surveillance* (ATOS) backbone to manage its sensors, combine their output in a tactical situation presented on up to four workstations.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] A tactical display is added to the glass cockpit and can be integrated with INS/GPS positioning systems and IFF transponder.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Three U/VHF radios, one HF radio and a wideband SATCOM are used for communications.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Other sensors, systems and communications equipment can be integrated, like an electronic support measure (ESM) system.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] A defensive aids sub-system (DASS) is optionally available for operation in hostile areas.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Its capabilities are airborne ocean surface surveillance, telemetry recording and relay.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] , the aircraft can detect a person in a life raft up to 128 km away in the water.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] It downlinks this telemetry data to a ground-based surveillance center which is to be integrated to the National Coast Watch Center system.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] It has the capability to relay four airborne UHF frequencies over the horizon to ground sites.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Additional Mission Management System (MMS), L-3 Wescam MX-20HD electro-optical sensor system for intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance (ISR) and Signals Intelligence (SIGINT) capabilities.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] of the -600, 8 November 2017 launch with 30 firm orders from FedEx plus 20 options.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] it was EASA certified by early December.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] FedEx should receive six aircraft per year until 2025, later freighters will fly in the US and in Latin America.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] ATR forecasts a market for 460 converted or new-build turboprop freighters over 20 years.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] Bulk Freighter (tube versions) and ULD Freighter (Large Cargo Door).
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] , coupled with a dedicated cargo conversion.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] A VIP version of the -500 is available with a luxury interior for executive or corporate transport.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] During the mid-1980s, the company investigated a 78-seat derivative of the ATR 72.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] ATR also studied a turbofan version of the proposed ATR 82 (stretched version of the ATR 72) in the early 1990s.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] This proposed version targeted the increasing demand of worldwide cargo and express mail markets, where the aim is to allow operators to supplement their passengers flights with freighter flights.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] In Quick Change configuration, the smoke detector is equipped alongside other modifications required in order to meet the certification for full freight operations.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] ft), facilitating containerised freight loading.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] It takes 30 minutes to convert the ATR 42, and 45 minutes to convert the ATR 72.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The ATR 72 has been involved in 66 aviation accidents and incidents, including 40 hull losses, resulting in 532 fatalities.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] As of August 2024, there have been 13 accidents with at least one fatality reported.
[src:glass-cockpit/atr-72] The first fatal accident involving the aircraft was American Eagle Flight 4184 on 31 October 1994, with 68 fatalities, while the most recent accident occurred on 9 August 2024 when Voepass Linhas Aéreas Flight 2283 crashed resulting in 62 fatalities.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] A **glass cockpit** is a cockpit, as used in aircraft and spacecraft, that features an array of electronic (digital) flight instrument displays, typically large LCD screens, rather than traditional analog dials and gauges.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] While a traditional cockpit relies on numerous mechanical gauges (nicknamed "steam gauges") to display information, a glass cockpit uses several multi-function displays and a primary flight display driven by flight management systems, that can be adjusted to show flight information as needed.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] This simplifies aircraft operation and navigation and allows pilots to focus only on the most pertinent information.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] They are also popular with airlines as they usually eliminate the need for a flight engineer, saving costs.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] In recent years the technology has also become widely available in small aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] As aircraft displays have modernized, the sensors that feed them have modernized as well.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Traditional gyroscopic flight instruments have been replaced by electronic attitude and heading reference systems (AHRS) and air data computers (ADCs), improving reliability and reducing cost and maintenance.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] GPS receivers are usually integrated into glass cockpits.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The Boeing 757 and 767-200/-300 introduced an electronic engine-indicating and crew-alerting system (EICAS) for monitoring engine performance while retaining mechanical gauges for airspeed, altitude and vertical speed.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Later glass cockpits, found in the Boeing 737NG, 747-400, 767-400, 777, Airbus A320, later Airbuses, Ilyushin Il-96 and Tupolev Tu-204 have completely replaced the mechanical gauges and warning lights in previous generations of aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Glass cockpits originated in military aircraft in the late 1960s and early 1970s; an early example is the Mark II avionics of the F-111D (first ordered in 1967, delivered from 1970 to 1973), which featured a multi-function display.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Prior to the 1970s, air transport operations were not considered sufficiently demanding to require advanced equipment like electronic flight displays.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Also, computer technology was not at a level where sufficiently light and powerful electronics were available.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The increasing complexity of transport aircraft, the advent of digital systems and the growing air traffic congestion around airports began to change that.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The Boeing 2707 was one of the earliest commercial aircraft designed with a glass cockpit.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Most cockpit instruments were still analog, but cathode-ray tube (CRT) displays were to be used for the attitude indicator and horizontal situation indicator (HSI).
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] However, the 2707 was cancelled in 1971 after insurmountable technical difficulties and ultimately the end of project funding by the US government.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] As a result, NASA conducted research on displays that could process the raw aircraft system and flight data into an integrated, easily understood picture of the flight situation, culminating in a series of flights demonstrating a full glass cockpit system.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The success of the NASA-led glass cockpit work is reflected in the total acceptance of electronic flight displays.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The safety and efficiency of flights have been increased with improved pilot understanding of the aircraft's situation relative to its environment (or "situational awareness").
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] By the end of the 1990s, liquid-crystal display (LCD) panels were increasingly favored among aircraft manufacturers because of their efficiency, reliability and legibility.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Earlier LCD panels suffered from poor legibility at some viewing angles and poor response times, making them unsuitable for aviation.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The glass cockpit has become standard equipment in airliners, business jets, and military aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] It was fitted into NASA's Space Shuttle orbiters *Atlantis*, *Columbia*, *Discovery*, and *Endeavour*, and the Russian Soyuz TMA model spacecraft that were launched for the first time in 2002.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] By the end of the century glass cockpits began appearing in general aviation aircraft as well.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] In 2003, Cirrus Design's SR20 and SR22 became the first light aircraft equipped with glass cockpits, which they made standard on all Cirrus aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] By 2005, even basic trainers like the Piper Cherokee and Cessna 172 were shipping with glass cockpits as options (which nearly all customers chose), as well as many modern utility aircraft such as the Diamond DA42.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II features a "panoramic cockpit display" touchscreen that replaces most of the switches and toggles found in an aircraft cockpit.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The civilian Cirrus Vision SF50 has the same, which they call a "Perspective Touch" glass cockpit.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Unlike the previous era of glass cockpits—where designers merely copied the look and feel of conventional electromechanical instruments onto cathode-ray tubes—the new displays represent a true departure.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] They look and behave very similarly to other computers, with windows and data that can be manipulated with point-and-click devices.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] They also add terrain, approach charts, weather, vertical displays, and 3D navigation images.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The improved concepts enable aircraft makers to customize cockpits to a greater degree than previously.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] All of the manufacturers involved have chosen to do so in one way or another—such as using a trackball, thumb pad or joystick as a pilot-input device in a computer-style environment.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Many of the modifications offered by the aircraft manufacturers improve situational awareness and customize the human-machine interface to increase safety.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Modern glass cockpits might include synthetic vision systems (SVS) or enhanced flight vision systems (EFVS).
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Synthetic vision systems display a realistic 3D depiction of the outside world (similar to a flight simulator), based on a database of terrain and geophysical features in conjunction with the attitude and position information gathered from the aircraft navigational systems.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Enhanced flight vision systems add real-time information from external sensors, such as an infrared camera.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] All new airliners such as the Airbus A380, Boeing 787 and private jets such as Bombardier Global Express and Learjet use glass cockpits.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Many modern general aviation (GA) aircraft are available with glass cockpits.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Systems such as the Garmin G1000 are now available on many new GA aircraft, including the classic Cessna 172 and more modern Cirrus SR22.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Many small aircraft can also be modified post-production to replace analogue instruments.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Glass cockpits are also popular as a retrofit for older private jets and turboprops such as Dassault Falcons, Raytheon Hawkers, Bombardier Challengers, Cessna Citations, Gulfstreams, King Airs, Learjets, Astras, and many others.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Aviation service companies work closely with equipment manufacturers to address the needs of the owners of these aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Today, smartphones and tablets use apps to remotely control complex devices, e.g. by Wi-Fi radio interface, demonstrating how the "glass cockpit" idea can be applied to consumer devices.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Applications include toy-grade UAVs which use the display and touch screen to employ every aspect of the "glass cockpit" for instrument display, and fly-by-wire for aircraft control.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The glass cockpit idea made news in 1980s trade magazines, like *Aviation Week & Space Technology*, when NASA announced that it would be replacing most of the electro-mechanical flight instruments in the space shuttles with glass cockpit components.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The articles mentioned how glass cockpit components had the added benefit of being a few hundred pounds lighter than the original flight instruments and support systems used in the Space Shuttles.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The Space Shuttle *Atlantis* was the first orbiter to be retrofitted with a glass cockpit in 2000 with the launch of STS-101.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] *Columbia* was the second orbiter with a glass cockpit on STS-109 in 2002, followed by *Discovery* in 2005 with STS-114, and *Endeavour* in 2007 with STS-118.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] NASA's Orion spacecraft will use glass cockpits derived from Boeing 787 Dreamliner.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] As aircraft operation depends on glass cockpit systems, flight crews must be trained to deal with failures.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The Airbus A320 family has seen fifty incidents where several flight displays were lost.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] On 25 January 2008, United Airlines Flight 731 experienced a serious glass-cockpit blackout, losing half of the Electronic Centralised Aircraft Monitor (ECAM) displays as well as all radios, transponders, Traffic Collision Avoidance System (TCAS), and attitude indicators.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The pilots were able to land at Newark Airport without radio contact in good weather and daylight conditions.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Airbus has offered an optional fix, which the US National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) has suggested to the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) as mandatory, but the FAA has yet to make it a requirement.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] A preliminary NTSB factsheet is available.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] Due to the possibility of a blackout, glass cockpit aircraft also have an integrated standby instrument system that includes (at a minimum) an artificial horizon, altimeter and airspeed indicator.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] It is electronically separate from the main instruments and can run for several hours on a backup battery.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] In 2010, the NTSB published a study done on 8,000 general aviation light aircraft.
[src:glass-cockpit/glass-cockpit] The study found that, although aircraft equipped with glass cockpits had a lower overall accident rate, they also had a larger chance of being involved in a fatal accident.
